JOHANNESBURG - Ratings agency Standard and Poor s has downgraded seven South African financial institutions.The agency says this was necessary as it cannot rank local banks above the foreign currency sovereign credit ratings.Banking stocks have lost value on the JSE since President Jacob Zuma s unpopular cabinet reshuffle.S&P Global downgraded the country s foreign currency credit rating on Monday.FNB, Nedbank, Investec, Absa and BNP Paribas SA are now feeling the knock-on effect.READ: Downgrade to junk a major setback, says deputy Reserve Bank governorThe agency says the country s downgrade will affect domestic banks' operations, including their ability to service foreign currency obligations.S&P Global says, amid slow economic growth and political turbulence, South African banks have been resilient.eNCA